#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:1
msgid "The MIR Importer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:3
msgid ""
"The previous chapters explained how rustc produces Stable MIR ([rustc_public]"
"(rustc-public.md)) and how pliron provides the IR framework ([Pliron](pliron."
"md)). This chapter is where the two meet: `mir-importer` takes the Stable "
"MIR that rustc hands us and translates it into `dialect-mir`, the pliron "
"dialect that preserves Rust semantics. The translator initially emits an "
"alloca/load/store form -- cheap to produce, easy to reason about, and a "
"pliron identity on input. A subsequent `pliron::opts::mem2reg` pass promotes "
"those slots back into SSA form. cuda-oxide then runs its [compiler "
"optimizations](compiler-optimizations.md), beginning with annotated loop "
"unrolling, before lowering to the LLVM dialect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:14
msgid ""
"But translation is only half the job. `mir-importer` also orchestrates the "
"*entire* compilation pipeline: translate, verify, optimize `dialect-mir`, "
"lower, export, and generate PTX. It is both the translator and the stage "
"manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:18
msgid "The crate lives in `crates/mir-importer` and is split into two parts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:20
msgid ""
"**`translator/`** -- the MIR-to-pliron translation logic (the interesting "
"part)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:21
msgid ""
"**`pipeline.rs`** -- the orchestration that chains every stage together (the "
"responsible part)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:26
msgid "Pipeline Orchestration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:28
msgid ""
"Before diving into translation details, here is the big picture. The "
"`run_pipeline()` function is the entry point that `rustc-codegen-cuda` calls "
"after collecting device functions. It takes a list of `CollectedFunction` "
"structs and a `PipelineConfig`, then runs these stages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:33
msgid ""
"Step 1:  Translate Rust MIR → `dialect-mir`\n"
"Step 2:  Verify `dialect-mir` module\n"
"Step 3:  Run `pliron::opts::mem2reg` to promote alloca slots back into SSA\n"
"Step 4:  Apply `dialect-mir` optimizations (currently annotated loop "
"unrolling)\n"
"Step 5:  Lower `dialect-mir` → LLVM dialect (via mir-lower)\n"
"Step 6:  For NVVM builds, adjust the LLVM dialect via nvvm-transforms\n"
"Step 7:  Export the LLVM dialect to textual LLVM IR (.ll)\n"
"Step 8:  Compile with llc, or with libNVVM and nvJitLink\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:44
msgid ""
"Full variable-debug builds skip steps 3 and 4 so source variables remain in "
"stable memory locations for cuda-gdb."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:47
msgid ""
"Each `CollectedFunction` carries everything the pipeline needs to know about "
"a device function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:50
msgid ""
"pub struct CollectedFunction {\n"
"    pub instance: Instance,\n"
"    pub is_kernel: bool,\n"
"    pub export_name: String,\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:58
msgid ""
"`instance` is the monomorphized function from `rustc_public`. `is_kernel` "
"distinguishes kernel entry points from device helper functions (kernels get "
"special metadata in the LLVM IR so the NVPTX backend emits them as `.entry` "
"points). `export_name` is the symbol name that appears in the final PTX -- "
"for device functions this is typically a fully qualified name (FQDN) that "
"matches what `CrateDef::name()` returns for the same function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:65
msgid "For each function, the pipeline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:67
msgid "Retrieves the MIR body via `instance.body()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:68
msgid ""
"Calls `translate_function()` to produce a pliron module containing the "
"`dialect-mir` representation (using `mir.alloca` slots for locals)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:70
msgid ""
"Runs pliron's verifier on the module to catch structural errors early -- "
"mismatched types, missing operands, broken dominance -- before they turn "
"into cryptic LLVM failures downstream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:73
msgid ""
"Runs `pliron::opts::mem2reg` to promote the alloca slots back into SSA "
"values within `dialect-mir`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:75
msgid ""
"Runs [compiler optimizations](compiler-optimizations.md), currently "
"unrolling supported loops carrying `#[unroll]` or `#[unroll(N)]` requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:77
msgid ""
"Runs `lower_mir_to_llvm` (from the `mir-lower` crate) to lower every "
"`dialect-mir` operation into its LLVM dialect equivalent via "
"`DialectConversion`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:80
msgid ""
"For NVVM builds, runs `nvvm-transforms` with the dialect selected for the "
"target GPU. Ordinary PTX builds skip this step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:82
msgid ""
"Exports the LLVM dialect module to a textual `.ll` string and compiles it "
"with `llc`, or with libNVVM and nvJitLink for NVVM output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:85
msgid ""
"If any step fails, the pipeline stops and returns a typed error (`NoBody`, "
"`Translation`, `Verification`, `Lowering`, `Export`, or `PtxGeneration`) "
"with enough context to diagnose the problem. No silent corruption, no "
"mysterious empty output files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:92
msgid "Translation Architecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:94
msgid ""
"The `translator/` directory is where Stable MIR becomes pliron IR. Each "
"module handles one level of MIR structure, and they compose neatly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Purpose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`body`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Function-level translation, alloca-slot seeding, FQDN name sanitization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`block`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Basic block translation coordinator"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`statement`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Statement translations (assignments, storage)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`terminator`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid ""
"Terminator translation (goto, call, return, FQDN-based intrinsic dispatch)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`rvalue`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Expression translation (binops, casts, aggregates)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`types`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "Rust type to `dialect-mir` type conversion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "`values`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:0
msgid "MIR local → alloca slot mapping (`ValueMap`) + slot addrspace inference"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:107
msgid "The call flow follows MIR's structure top-down:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:109
msgid ""
"translate_function()\n"
"  └─ body::translate_body()\n"
"       ├─ emit_entry_allocas()            // one mir.alloca per non-ZST "
"local\n"
"       │     └─ SlotAddrSpaceMap::analyze // pointer slot addrspace "
"inference\n"
"       └─ For each basic block:\n"
"            └─ block::translate_block()\n"
"                  ├─ statement::translate_statement()\n"
"                  │     └─ rvalue::translate_rvalue()\n"
"                  └─ terminator::translate_terminator()\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:121
msgid ""
"`translate_body()` sets up the function's signature, creates pliron blocks "
"corresponding to MIR basic blocks, sanitizes the function name (converting "
"`::` to `__` in the FQDN from `instance.name()`), emits one `mir.alloca` per "
"non-ZST local at the top of the entry block, and stores the incoming "
"function arguments into their respective slots. Every non-entry block is "
"left argument-less -- cross-block data flow is carried by the alloca slots, "
"not by block arguments. Then it walks each block sequentially, translating "
"statements and terminators one by one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:130
msgid ""
"`translate_statement()` handles the flat operations within a block -- "
"assignments, storage live/dead markers, and discriminant writes. When an "
"assignment involves a right-hand side expression (a MIR `Rvalue`), it "
"delegates to `translate_rvalue()`, which handles binary operations, unary "
"operations, casts, aggregate construction, discriminant reads, pointer "
"arithmetic, and the other dozen-odd things Rust compiles to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:137
msgid ""
"`translate_terminator()` handles the block-ending operations: `Goto`, "
"`SwitchInt`, `Call`, `Return`, `Assert`, `Drop`, and `Unreachable`. This is "
"also where intrinsic dispatch lives -- but that gets its own section below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:143
msgid "The SSA Challenge (and how we defer it)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:145
msgid ""
"This is the trickiest part of the translation, and it deserves careful "
"explanation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:148
msgid ""
"Rust MIR is *not* in strict SSA form. Locals (variables) are named storage "
"locations that any block can read or write. If `_3` is assigned in `bb0`, it "
"can be freely used in `bb1`, `bb5`, or anywhere else -- MIR does not care."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:152
msgid ""
"Pliron IR (MLIR-like) ultimately expects **strict SSA**: a value must "
"dominate every use, and if a value needs to flow from one block to another, "
"it must be passed explicitly as a **block argument**. You cannot just reach "
"across blocks and grab a local."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:157
msgid "We resolve this tension in two phases:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:159
msgid ""
"**Importer: alloca + load/store.** The `mir-importer` deliberately does "
"*not* construct SSA directly. Every non-ZST MIR local is backed by a single "
"stack slot -- one `mir.alloca` emitted at the top of the entry block and "
"recorded in `ValueMap`. Every write to the local becomes a `mir.store` into "
"its slot; every read becomes a `mir.load`. Branch terminators are therefore "
"all **zero-operand** and every non-entry block is **argument-less**: all "
"cross-block data flow travels through the alloca slots, not through block "
"arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:168
msgid ""
"**`pliron::opts::mem2reg`: slots → SSA.** After the `dialect-mir` module "
"verifies, `pipeline.rs` runs pliron's built-in `mem2reg` pass. It promotes "
"every eligible alloca back into SSA values, rewiring each load to the "
"reaching definition and inserting block arguments (the pliron spelling of "
"phi nodes) wherever a value merges along multiple control paths. Address-"
"taken slots -- the ones we genuinely need to keep on the stack -- are left "
"alone for the `dialect-mir` → LLVM dialect lowering to translate into real "
"`alloca`s."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:177
msgid ""
"Here is the problem in miniature. Given MIR where `_1` is written in `bb0` "
"and read in `bb1`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:180
msgid ""
"// Rust MIR\n"
"bb0: { _1 = 42_i32; goto -> bb1; }\n"
"bb1: { _0 = _1;     return; }\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:186
msgid ""
"The importer first emits this alloca-based `dialect-mir` (before `mem2reg`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:188
msgid ""
"^bb0:\n"
"  %s1 = mir.alloca           : !mir.ptr<i32>\n"
"  %c  = mir.constant 42_i32  : i32\n"
"  mir.store %c, %s1\n"
"  mir.goto ^bb1                     // zero-operand; _1 flows via %s1\n"
"^bb1:                               // no block arguments\n"
"  %r = mir.load %s1 : i32\n"
"  mir.return %r : i32\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:199
msgid ""
"After `pliron::opts::mem2reg` has promoted `%s1`, the same function becomes "
"SSA-form `dialect-mir`, with block arguments appearing only where they are "
"actually needed to merge reaching definitions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:203
msgid ""
"^bb0:\n"
"  %c = mir.constant 42_i32 : i32\n"
"  mir.goto ^bb1(%c : i32)\n"
"^bb1(%r : i32):\n"
"  mir.return %r : i32\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:211
msgid ""
"(Functions with a single-predecessor successor, like the example above, end "
"up with a single block argument; joins with multiple reaching definitions "
"are where `mem2reg` introduces the nontrivial phi-style arguments.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:215
msgid ""
"The upshot: the importer never runs a liveness analysis and never threads "
"values across blocks. All \"which value is live where?\" reasoning is "
"deferred to `mem2reg`, which already solves it correctly for the entire "
"`dialect-mir` module in one pass. The `translator/terminator/mod.rs` module "
"docstring carries the same worked example in inline-source form for quick "
"reference."
msgstr ""

