#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:241
msgid "Dynamic struct layout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:243
msgid ""
"Here is a subtlety that saves users a real headache. Consider this struct:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:245
msgid ""
"struct Extreme {\n"
"    a: u8,\n"
"    b: i128,\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:252
msgid "Rust's layout algorithm may reorder fields for alignment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:254
msgid ""
"User writes:      struct Extreme { a: u8, b: i128 }\n"
"rustc may layout: [b: i128 @ offset 0][a: u8 @ offset 16]\n"
"MirStructType:    mem_to_decl mapping, offsets, total_size\n"
"LLVM struct:      { i128, i8, [15 x i8] }   // explicit padding\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:261
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide queries rustc for the exact byte offset of every field and builds "
"the struct type with explicit padding bytes. The `MirStructType` stores a "
"`mem_to_decl` mapping (memory order to declaration order), per-field "
"offsets, and the total size. When lowered to LLVM, padding is materialized "
"as `[N x i8]` arrays between fields."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:267
msgid ""
"The practical upshot: **`#[repr(C)]` is not required** for types shared "
"between host and device code. cuda-oxide matches rustc's layout "
"automatically, so your structs can use Rust's default `repr(Rust)` layout "
"and the compiler will Do The Right Thing on both sides. One less attribute "
"to remember, one less footgun to step on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:275
msgid "Intrinsic Dispatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:277
msgid ""
"When the translator encounters a `Call` terminator, it does not immediately "
"emit a `mir.call` operation. First, it checks whether the callee is a *known "
"intrinsic* -- a function from `cuda_device` that maps directly to a GPU "
"hardware instruction rather than a function with a body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:282
msgid ""
"The `try_dispatch_intrinsic()` function matches on the **fully qualified "
"domain name (FQDN)** of the callee, obtained from `CrateDef::name()`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:285
msgid ""
"match name {\n"
"    \"cuda_device::thread::threadIdx_x\" => "
"emit_nvvm_intrinsic(ReadPtxSregTidXOp),\n"
"    \"cuda_device::warp::shuffle_xor\"   => "
"emit_warp_shuffle_i32(ShflSyncBflyI32Op),\n"
"    \"cuda_device::sync::syncthreads\"   => "
"emit_nvvm_intrinsic(Barrier0Op),\n"
"    // ... 100+ intrinsics\n"
"    _ => translate_as_normal_call()\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:295
msgid ""
"The full FQDN (e.g. `cuda_device::thread::threadIdx_x`, not just "
"`threadIdx_x`) is used for matching to avoid ambiguity between identically-"
"named functions in different modules. The same FQDN is also used as the call "
"target name for non-generic, non-intrinsic calls -- the collector produces "
"matching names, and the lowering layer converts `::` to `__` on both sides."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:301
msgid ""
"If the function is a recognized intrinsic, the translator emits the "
"corresponding `dialect-nvvm` operation directly -- no function body, no call "
"overhead, just the hardware instruction. Thread indexing, warp shuffles, "
"barriers, shared memory operations, TMA bulk copies, and matrix multiply "
"instructions all go through this path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:307
msgid ""
"If the function is *not* an intrinsic, it falls through to the normal path: "
"emit a `mir.call` operation that references the callee by symbol name. The "
"callee's body will have been translated separately (it is in the collected "
"function list too), so everything links up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:313
msgid ""
"The intrinsic dispatch table is the main extension point for adding new GPU "
"operations to cuda-oxide. If NVIDIA ships a new instruction and you want to "
"expose it, you add a function to `cuda_device`, add a `dialect-nvvm` op, and "
"add a match arm here. See [Adding New Intrinsics](adding-new-intrinsics.md) "
"for a step-by-step guide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:322
msgid "Handling Unwind Paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:324
msgid ""
"MIR models Rust's panic semantics faithfully. Every function call has two "
"possible successors -- a return target and an unwind target:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:327
msgid "_2 = mul(_1, _3) -> [return: bb1, unwind: bb2]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:331
msgid ""
"On a CPU, the unwind path matters: it runs destructors, unwinds the stack, "
"and either catches the panic or aborts the process. On a GPU, the CUDA "
"toolchain does not expose this capability today -- nvcc/ptxas strip landing "
"pads and no exception-handling infrastructure survives to PTX. The hardware "
"itself *could* support unwinding (absolute branches + per-thread call stack "
"tracking post-Volta are sufficient), but the compiler and runtime do not "
"wire it up. NVIDIA has an active project to add C++ exception support for "
"automotive safety; the current cuda-oxide design is forward-compatible with "
"that work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:340
msgid ""
"For now, cuda-oxide treats **all unwind paths as unreachable**. If a panic "
"would occur at runtime -- say, an integer overflow in debug mode or an "
"explicit `panic!()` -- the GPU traps and the kernel crashes. This is "
"semantically equivalent to `panic=abort` without requiring the user to set "
"the flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:346
msgid ""
"In practice, the translator simply ignores the unwind target in every `Call` "
"and `Assert` terminator, generating only the return-path branch. The unwind "
"blocks are never translated. They vanish, like they were never there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:350
msgid ""
"This is not as scary as it sounds. Rust's borrow checker and type system "
"prevent most of the bugs that would cause panics. And for the ones that slip "
"through (array bounds checks, unwrap on `None`), a GPU trap is the correct "
"behavior anyway -- there is nothing useful a GPU thread can do to "
"\"recover\" from a logic error mid-kernel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:358
msgid "Putting It All Together"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:360
msgid ""
"Let's trace a simple kernel through the full pipeline to see how all the "
"pieces connect. Here is a vector addition kernel:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:363
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn vecadd(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    let idx = thread::index_1d();\n"
"    if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(idx) {\n"
"        *c_elem = a[idx.get()] + b[idx.get()];\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:373
msgid ""
"After `mir-importer` translates the Stable MIR into `dialect-mir` (and "
"`pliron::opts::mem2reg` has promoted the alloca slots back into SSA), the "
"result looks something like this (simplified, with many details elided for "
"clarity):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:378
msgid ""
"mir.func @vecadd(%a: mir.slice<f32>, %b: mir.slice<f32>,\n"
"                 %c: mir.disjoint_slice<f32>) {\n"
"^entry:\n"
"    %idx = nvvm.read_ptx_sreg_tid_x : i32\n"
"    %len = mir.extract_field %c[1]       // slice length\n"
"    %in_bounds = mir.lt %idx, %len\n"
"    mir.cond_br %in_bounds, ^compute, ^exit\n"
"\n"
"^compute:\n"
"    %a_val = mir.load ...                // a[idx]\n"
"    %b_val = mir.load ...                // b[idx]\n"
"    %sum = mir.add %a_val, %b_val : f32\n"
"    mir.store %sum, ...                  // c[idx] = sum\n"
"    mir.goto ^exit\n"
"\n"
"^exit:\n"
"    mir.return\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:399
msgid "A few things to notice:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:401
msgid ""
"**`thread::index_1d()`** was dispatched as an intrinsic and became `nvvm."
"read_ptx_sreg_tid_x` -- a direct GPU register read, not a function call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:404
msgid ""
"**`DisjointSlice::get_mut()`** turned into a bounds check (`mir.lt`) and a "
"conditional branch. The `if let Some` pattern in Rust became explicit "
"control flow."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:407
msgid ""
"**Block arguments** are absent here. Remember that `mir-importer` itself "
"emits *every* branch terminator with zero operands and every non-entry block "
"argument-less -- values cross block boundaries through alloca slots until "
"`pliron::opts::mem2reg` runs. In this function, `mem2reg` can see that "
"nothing needs to merge at `^compute` or `^exit` (no values survive across "
"the branch), so it promotes the slots away without introducing any block "
"arguments. A loopier kernel with values that live across a back edge would "
"end up with `mir.goto ^header(%i, %acc)` and `^header(%i: i32, %acc: f32)` "
"after `mem2reg`, which is pliron's spelling of phi nodes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:417
msgid ""
"**No unwind paths.** The original MIR had unwind targets on every operation "
"that could panic. They are gone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:420
msgid "From here, the pipeline takes over:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:422
msgid ""
"**Verify** -- pliron checks that every operation's types match, every "
"block's arguments are correct, and dominance holds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:424
msgid ""
"**Optimize** -- `mir-transforms` rewrites supported annotated loops and "
"cleans up the control flow it changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:426
msgid ""
"**Lower** -- `lower_mir_to_llvm` transforms `mir.add` into `llvm.fadd`, `mir."
"load` into `llvm.load`, `mir.slice` into an LLVM struct of pointer and "
"length, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:429
msgid ""
"**Prepare NVVM IR when needed** -- `nvvm-transforms` converts operations to "
"the LLVM form accepted by the selected libNVVM target. Ordinary PTX builds "
"skip this step."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:432
msgid ""
"**Export** -- the LLVM dialect is printed as a textual `.ll` file with the "
"appropriate `!nvvm.annotations` metadata marking `vecadd` as a kernel entry "
"point."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:435
msgid ""
"**Compile** -- LLVM's NVPTX backend normally compiles the `.ll` to `.ptx`. "
"NVVM builds instead use libNVVM and nvJitLink. The result is written next to "
"the host binary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../compiler/mir-importer.md:439
msgid ""
"`dialect-mir` captures Rust semantics faithfully. Before lowering it, cuda-"
"oxide can perform targeted, behavior-preserving rewrites. The first is "
"explained in [Compiler Optimizations](compiler-optimizations.md). The "
"[Lowering Pipeline](lowering-pipeline.md) then converts the result into "
"something LLVM can understand."
msgstr ""
